
<!-- Prevention tips -->
<section aria-labelledby="prevention-tips-title" class="prevention-wrapper">
    <div class="prevention-content">
    <h4 id="prevention-tips-title">Prevention tips</h4>

    <div class="tips-group">
        <h5>When outdoors</h5>
        <ul>
            <li>Wear long sleeves and long trousers in grassy, wooded, or brushy areas.</li>
            <li>Choose light-coloured clothing so ticks are easier to spot.</li>
            <li>Use an appropriate insect repellent on exposed skin and clothing.</li>
            <li>Stick to clear paths and avoid brushing directly against tall grass or shrubs where possible.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="tips-group">
        <h5>After returning home</h5>
        <ul>
            <li>Check your skin carefully, especially warm, hidden areas (behind knees, armpits, waistline, scalp).</li>
            <li>Shower within a couple of hours to help remove loose ticks.</li>
            <li>Inspect pets that have been outside, especially around ears, neck, and paws.</li>
            <li>Put outdoor clothes in a hot wash to help kill any ticks that might be on fabric.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="tips-group">
        <h5>If you find a tick</h5>
        <ul>
            <li>Use tweezers or a tick-removal tool to grasp the tick as close to the skin as possible.</li>
            <li>Pull upwards steadily without twisting or crushing the tick.</li>
            <li>Clean the bite area with soap and water or an alcohol wipe afterwards.</li>
            <li>Monitor the area for any rash or signs of feeling unwell and seek medical advice if you are concerned.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>
